04933nam a22008175i 9781442694491DE-B159720190516114113.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||190516s2018    onc    fo  d z      eng d  a97814426944917 a10.3138/97814426944912doi  a(DE-B1597)496350  a(OCoLC)1020621180  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  aonccCA-ON 4aBS2860.N6bB85 2017eb 7aLIT0042502bisacsh 7aLIT0110002bisacsh 7aREL0330002bisacsh04a229/.82231 aBullitta, Dario , eauthor.10aNidrstigningar Saga :bSources, Transmission, and Theology of the Old Norse "Descent into Hell" /cDario Bullitta. 1aToronto : bUniversity of Toronto Press, c[2018] 4c©2017  a1 online resource :b3 figures  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aToronto Old Norse-Icelandic Series (TONIS)00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tIllustrations and Tables -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction -- tAbbreviations -- t1. The Latin Evangelium Nicodemi in Medieval Europe -- t2. The Manuscript Tradition of Niðrstigningar saga -- t3. The Manuscript Filiation of Niðrstigningar saga -- t4. The Latin Source Text Underlying Niðrstigningar saga -- t5. The Textual Interpolations of Niðrstigningar saga -- t6. The Theological Context of Niðrstigningar saga -- t7. Conclusion -- tNotes -- tTexts -- tTranslations -- tBibliography -- tIndex of Scriptural Quotations -- tIndex of Manuscripts -- tGeneral Index -- tToronto Old Norse and Icelandic Series  aThe Evangelium Nicodemi, or Gospel of Nicodemus, was the most widely circulated apocryphal writing in medieval Europe. It depicted the trial, Passion, and crucifixion of Christ as well as his Harrowing of Hell. During the twelfth-century renaissance, some exemplars of the Evangelium Nicodemi found their way to Iceland where its text was later translated into the vernacular and known as Niðrstigningar saga. Dario Bullitta has embarked on a highly fascinating voyage that traces the routes of transmission of the Latin text to Iceland and continental Scandinavia. He argues that the saga is derived from a less popular twelfth-century French redaction of the Evangelium Nicodemi, and that it bears the exegetical and scriptural influences of twelfth-century Parisian scholars active at Saint Victor, Peter Comestor and Peter Lombard in particular. By placing Niðrstigningar saga within the greater theological and homiletical context of early thirteenth-century Iceland, Bullitta successfully adds to our knowledge of the early reception of Latin biblical and apocryphal literature in medieval Iceland and provides a new critical edition and translation of the vernacular text.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 16. Mai 2019) 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / European / Scandinavian.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2018 Englishz978311060425208iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2018z9783110603255oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Literary, Cultural and Area Stud. 2018 Englishz978311060418408iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Literary, Cultural and Area Studies 2018z9783110603187oZDB-23-DKU08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Toronto Press ebook package 2017z978311063896740uhttps://doi.org/10.3138/9781442694491423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9781442694491.jpg  a978-3-11-060418-4  EBOOK PACKAGE Literary, Cultural and Area Stud. 2018 Englishb2018  a978-3-11-060425-2  EBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2018 Englishb2018  a978-3-11-063896-7  University of Toronto Press ebook package 2017b2017  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_LT  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_LT  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA14ALL